description: A chronic autoimmune disease that affects the skin, joints, kidneys, and other organs. SLE causes a maculopapular rash, proteinuria, thrombocytopenia, and pleural effusion. It is diagnosed through a combination of physical exam, blood tests, imaging, and biopsy. Treatment includes immunosuppressive medications and corticosteroids.
prevalence: 0.3-2.7 per 1,000 women 1.1-3.6 per 100,000 in general population
risk factors: Female gender, African American race, family history, exposure to certain medications or chemicals
symptoms: Fever, fatigue, weight loss, rash, joint pain and swelling, swelling in the hands and feet, hair loss, seizures, mental health changes, pleurisy, kidney problems
tests: ANA test, anti-dsDNA test, full blood count, C3 and C4 complement levels, antiphospholipid antibodies
prognosis: Variable: depends on disease severity and presence of organ damage, with 85% survival at 10 years
